Also - although I don't know why I'm being serious for a moment in the Lounge - I'm not going to join in any dog-pile on the OP. I think it's a pretty normal and understandable reaction (as unfortunate as that may or may not be). However, I would like to point out something to everyone 'defending' him:My mom basically professed the same type of thing after I came out (she'd suspected for quite a while): "I was fine with *you*, I was just worried about what you'd go through!"Let me tell you, kids pick up on fucking *every* thing - those type of words, as well meaning and perhaps even as true as they might be, do not help. She may have even believed it herself when she said them, but all I heard was a cover for a small core of what I felt she really thought. When all a kid wants to hear from you is, "You're gay, really?! That's awesome, honey! I'd always hoped but I wasn't sure! I love you so much! Hey, everyone - did you hear? I did get the gay son I'd always wanted - fucking RAD! " - anything short will probably feel like a knife in the gut...no matter how well-meaning.Anyway, just a cautionary tale to parents...even if the only thing behind "I hope my son isn't gay/I'm so relieived he's not..." is that wish that your kid has an easier life, your kid is likely only going to internalize the first part - "My parents don't want me to be who I am. " Even if it is never specifically verbalized, if your kid's in this situation, I guarantee they are watching you like a hawk for any little clue about your potential feelings on the matter - off-hand comments, reading your posts on a web forum, whatever. As far as having an easier life goes...in my case being gay itself was orders of magnitude easier to deal with than spending years 10-20 building up silent fear/shame/anger because you aren't 100% rock-solidly convinced that your parents *really* love you or will love you for 'you'.
